<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06308096 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06308096 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  TRAVEL  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  SPEND a weekend listening to tall tales and fabulous fables about magicalspiders, swamp creatures and dudes such as Stagger Lee, High John theConqueror and John Henry. But you'll have to get to South Carolina first --specifically, Horry and Georgetown counties, for the Ninth National Festivalof Black Storytelling, &quot;Southern Lives, Southern Stories,&quot; Nov. 14-17. Amateurand professional storytellers and just plain old listeners will gather at fivelocations for workshops, performances and story swaps.;   Tellers and theirtales are in the African and African-American oral tradition and encompassghost stories and creation stories, morality tales, epics and history. &quot;Thetraditions are all so different,&quot; says spokesman Zack Hamlett III, &quot;comingfrom different parts of Africa and the Caribbean. But most of the tellers haveSouthern roots in common.&quot;  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Travel  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  STAGGER LEE SHOT BILLY; HEAR THE TALE TOLD AGAIN  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Travelers' Advisory  </MEMO><TEXT>     Tickets for the event, sponsored by the National Association of BlackStorytellers, are $25 for adults, $15 for students (with discounts forregistration by Friday); &quot;elders&quot; (65 and over) and kids (14 and under) arefree. Information: (800) 868-2787.; Gay dive trips;   (box) UnderseaExpeditions is organizing scuba excursions for gay divers. &quot;There's nothingmore uncomfortable than spending the day on a boat with a group of strangerswhose attitude about gays is a mystery,&quot; says company founder ChristianWinkle.;   Tours target the best dive spots at optimal season, says Winkle,stay in gay-friendly resorts and are led by dive masters who know the localwaters. Upcoming one-week trips to Belize (Dec. 7-14), Bonaire (Jan. 26-Feb.1), Baja California (Feb. 15- 22) and Key West (March 14-21) cost from $1,199to $2,199, based on double occupancy, including accommodations, boat diving,meals and air fare from the West Coast.;   More expeditions are scheduledlater in the year to Fiji, the Red Sea and the Great Barrier Reef, and openwater certification is available on most trips. For more information: UnderseaExpeditions, 291 Geary St., Suite 619, San Francisco 94102; (415) 398-2189.;Romania;   The State Department reports conditions have improved in Romania.Americans no longer need to defer travel there, but should exercise cautionand avoid demonstrations.; (hbox);   Twelve bed-and-breakfast inns in NorthernCalifornia are donating 10 percent of their profits to the Touch Romania(foster children's) Fund for each stay of two or more nights January throughMarch. To reserve, call Wine Country Inns of Sonoma County at (800) 354-4743.;Belize;   Visitors to Belize in Central America should exercise caution toavoid becoming crime victims, says a travel advisory from the StateDepartment.;   While the vast majority of the thousands of tourists andbusiness travelers who visit Belize each year experience no problems, the Oct.22 advisory states, robberies and related assaults have increased.; Passportfees;   The fee for a 10-year passport increased from $35 to $55 on Friday Achild's passport, good for five years, increased from $20 to $30. In addition,first-time applicants must pay an execution fee, which rose from $7 to $10.Applicants with a current or recently expired passport may apply for a new oneby mail; others must apply in person.; Potatoes;   What can you do with apotato? Power a clock, get 35 percent of your Vitamin C, do as the Incas anduse one to tell time, or take a baked one, slice it and tie it in a sockaround your neck -- that was an old-time cure for a sore throat. Or you coulduse the potato as a good excuse to head for Ottawa and view the newly reopenedNational Museum of Science and Technology, a great museum that includes hugelocomotives, Canada's space achievements, computers and much more.;   Rightnow they're featuring &quot;The Amazing Potato,&quot; which tells not only how to powera clock but how the potato changed the way the world ate. Did you know thathalf of Canada's potato crop becomes French fries or that the Dutch potatoindustry is worth more than its famed tulip production? For information onthis museum, call (613) 991-3044.; Australia;   Two and a half months afterPearl Harbor, nearly 200 Japanese aircraft attacked the northern Australianport city of Darwin. The 50th anniversary of what came to be known as theBattle of Australia will be commemorated Feb. 19, and the Northern Territorywill hold related events throughout 1992.;   About 60,000 U.S. troops helpedrepel the Japanese, and a memorial committee hopes that Americans will jointhe observances. A list of memorial events can be obtained from the NorthernTerritory Tourist Commission by calling (800) 468-8222.  </TEXT><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911103  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Sunday  </DAY><MONTH>  November  </MONTH><PG.COL>  3T  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  764  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Sunday, November 3, 199100308096,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>